22","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Longford, Wiltshire, England":"Longford, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Waleran","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Walburn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walburn","meanings":["English (Durham and North Yorkshire): habitational name from Walburn in Downholme (North Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>wala</i>, genitive plural of <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’, + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’. Alternatively, the name may derive from the Old French personal name <i>Walebron</i>, perhaps itself from ancient Germanic <i>Waldbrand</i> (<i>wald</i> ‘power, rule’ + <i>brand</i> ‘sword’)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":27,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":58,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":83,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":96,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":105,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Waleran was born about 1232, in Yorkshire, England, his father, William Waleran, was 44 and his mother, Isabel de Kilpek, was 21. He married Alice or Ellen De Meriet about 1256, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1232–":"umbes 1232–Surnud","1222–1298":"1222–1298","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1235–1309":"1235–1309","1237–1312":"1237–1312","1236–Female":"1236–Surnud","1258–1286":"1258–1286","1190–1273":"1190–1273","1213–1284":"1213–1284","1286":"1286","1284":"1284","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1237":"1237","1258":"1258","1236":"1236","1213":"1213","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","1453":"1453","1232":"1232","1298":"1298","about 1258":"umbes 1258","about 1256